<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-495-800  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 495 800.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  May 21 1990 v4 n20 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>House committees question USPS' automation project. (United StatesPostal Service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kellner, Mark A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Members of the House of Representatives Postal Operations andPostal Personnel and Management subcommittees are concerned abouthow the US Postal Service is managing the impact of the newautomation project on USPS workers.andP;  Committee members indicatedto Deputy Postmaster General Michael S. Coughlin that they wereupset that USPS workers were not being informed of the effectautomation will have on specific jobs.andP;  Committee members werealso concerned that the deployment of automation and lack ofworkers' familiarity with the equipment brought about delays inmail delivery in Dec 1989.andP;  Coughlin said the delays were due tothe volume of hand-addressed greeting cards and severe cold in theMidwest, not to problems with automation.andP;  Members of thecommittees are also concerned that the USPS is not working withthe postal workers union and management representatives.andP;  Couglinsaid a number of meetings have been held.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Postal ServiceMail ProcessingNational GovernmentGovernment OfficialsAutomationImpact AnalysisProject Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>